## Constraints

Things that must not be violated without an explicit PM decision. Agents read this and treat constraints as hard boundaries.

- <e.g., "Only Postgres — no additional databases. Reason: operational simplicity, single backup target.">
- <e.g., "No external services in hot path — everything must work offline. Reason: embedded deployment.">
- <e.g., "No background threads outside the worker pool — reason: reproducibility in tests.">

## Security constraints

- <e.g., "Passwords: bcrypt min cost 12, never stored plain, never logged">
- <e.g., "API keys: env vars only, never in source, never in response bodies or headers">
- <e.g., "User input: validated and sanitized before any DB query or shell invocation">
- <e.g., "Tokens: short-lived, not stored client-side beyond session">

## Code conventions

### AI-specific minimums

These exist because AI tends to write monolithic files and complex functions. Adjust if project has legitimate exceptions (generated code, data files).

- Max source file: 300 lines
- Max function / method: 50 lines
- Cyclomatic complexity: max 10 per function
- No file-level lint suppressions (only line- or function-level with comment)
- New code test coverage: min 80%

